Neosporin can cause #allergies, which disrupts the #wound #healing process, due to its main ingredient neomycin.

What is #keratosispilaris?

Keratosis pilaris or what some people call #chickenskin or #strawberryskin is a common skin condition that causes small, hard bumps to form on the skin. These bumps typically appear on the upper arms, thighs, and buttocks, but can also occur on the face and other parts of the body. The bumps are caused by the accumulation of #keratin, a protein found in the skin hair and nails, around the hair follicles.

Keratosis pilaris is NOT contagious - this is a question I get asked quite a bit! I often see it in children and teens, and tends to improve or resolve on its own as a person gets older. It is not curable, but can definitely be managed with proper #skincare and treatment!

Symptoms of keratosis pilaris include rough, bumpy skin, dry skin, and mild itching. The condition can be made worse by dry weather and hot baths, and may be more noticeable during the winter months.

If you do experience #frostbite please keep the following in mind:

- slowly rewarm in lukewarm water, do not place in hot water as the affected extremity is likely NUMB and could inadvertently get burned by water that’s too hot

- seek care immediately if any tissue is black or necrotic, if rewarming is not improving the blood flow, if there are wounds or sores in the skin

- don’t pop #blisters; if they pop naturally keep the blister roof on as a biological dressing

Stay safe! #dermbypark #winterskincare #skincare

Don’t believe everything you read on the Internet…sometimes #skincaremyths sound appealing but they’re simply not true.

1. How much 💧 you need depends on your size, how much water you’re losing to the environment and your kidney function. If you excessively drink 💧 all you’re going to do is go to the bathroom frequently

2. That squeaky clean feeling may actually be drying out your skin especially during winter time. Opt for a hydrating cleanser instead.

3. Poison Ivy is natural. It occurs naturally in the environment. But it’s not good for your skin; actually, the exact opposite. Look at ingredients in products not simply if something is labeled natural or not.

#Eczema is one of the most common conditions we see in our dermatology clinics. We don’t know exactly what causes it but it’s probably a combination of genetics and environmental exposures. It tends to flare in the winter time when your skin is the most dry and it appears in skin folds like your neck and insides of your elbows and backs of the knees. The itching can be incredibly bad, and the more you scratch, the higher the risk for the eczema to flare and for the skin to get infected. My husband and son both suffer from this, so we are constantly dealing with flares! Head to part two for treatments! #dermbypark #atopicdermatitis #rash #dermatitis #eczemaawarenesse #eczemaflareup

#eczema treatments depend on the severity of your disease. 

For mild cases of eczema, we will start with really thick moisturizers and lots of education around how to keep your skin barrier intact and strong. We may use over the counter to low strength topical steroids sparingly for one to two weeks at a time (it is NOT a long term solution). 

If that does not work, we can always escalate therapy to mid or high strength topical steroids depending on the location of the eczema on your body. 

We also have at our disposal non-steroid medication‘s that help to calm down inflammation like Protopic or Elidel; these can sting so I recommend mixing with Vaseline and keeping it in the fridge to make them more tolerable.

Photo therapy is another nonmedicated option to decrease inflammation in the skin. Anti-histamine pills can be used to control itching. 

We also have to Dupixent, which is an injectable biologic medication that is reserved for severe refractory eczema. I never use oral steroids for eczema. 

Have any questions about eczema? Leave them below #dermbypark #atopicdermatitis #eczemaawareness

Let’s talk about #nail health, especially with manicures at nail salons! Cuticles exist for a reason, acting as a small flap of skin to protect the boundary between nail plate and proximal nail fold. Cuticles are so important to keep microbes and irritants from getting under the skin, so don’t let anyone touch or cut your cuticles! #gelnails should be removed properly, not partially filed off, which can cause damage to the nail plate. Lastly, new research has come out that repeated exposure to radiation from nail drying lamps increases risk of DNA 🧬 damage. I recommend my patients who get frequent manicures to put sunscreen 🧴 on their hands before heading to the nail salon. 

How often do you go to the nail salon and do these facts surprise you? 

Source: Zhivagui, M., Hoda, A., Valenzuela, N. et al. DNA damage and somatic mutations in mammalian cells after irradiation with a nail polish dryer. Nat Commun 14, 276 (2023). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-023-35876-8

Let’s talk about #acne. Many many things cause #acneflares like genetics, hormones, bacterial load, and environmental exposures. Diet can contribute too! Food with high glycemic index (foods that spike your glucose levels quickly), skim milk, and whey protein have been found in studies to be associated with acne flares. Don’t forget to shower after working out to combat face and body acne, and make sure to wash your pillowcases regularly too - you’d be surprised how dirty those get, especially if youre sleeping on them with wet hair (I don’t recommend doing this!) The more you know!

Let’s talk about airplane ✈️ skin care! Today I am just covering INCREASED exposure to UV radiation in the plane. A research study in JAMA DERM from 2015 measured amount of UV radiation in airplane cockpits during flight and compared them to UVA carcinogenic affective doses in tanning beds. Turns out you get a heck of a lot of UV exposure as a pilot. When we’re sitting in the back, make sure to wear sunscreen or keep your window shut to reduce exposure to UVA during your flight. After all, you don’t want 1/2 of your face getting more sun ☀️ damage than the other! The more you know!

Body dysmorphic disorder #bdd related #tanning has been studied, and the authors pointed out how concerning it was that subjects were tanning to improve the BDD-related appearance “defects.” 

They shared that in their experience, BDD patients may tan to make uneven skin a more even color, to hide #acne and blemishes, as well as wrinkles. 

We know that tanning actually worsens hyperpigmentation and wrinkle formation. 

This is one reason among many why tanning is so dangerous

A few pearls about jock itch: fungus likes to thrive in warm, moist environments, and it can spread from one part of your body to another. 

*Change your underwear daily

* Dry skin folds THOROUGHLY after showering. I've even recommended patients to use their blow dryer on the cold setting before, especially if you have a lot of skin laxity in the area

* If you have athletes foot, put on socks 🧦 before, pulling your underwear up, to avoid spreading the fungus from your feet to your privates!

Hope these tips help! Linking another tinea-related post in my stories about how to prevent yourself from catching tinea in the summertime.

Back with more #eczema tips! As the weather gets colder dry skin is flaring and we need to make some adjustments.

As I mentioned before, in previous posts, my husband and son both suffer from eczema, so we adhere to a lot of these tips year around. 

- use skin care products that soothe the skin, calm itch, and repair the skin barrier (ingredients in the video)

- avoiding itchy clothing, material, like wool, as well as turtlenecks, or shawl collars, or any clothing that would cause extra itchiness around the neck and other skin folds

- using fragrance free products, including skin care, bath, products, and laundry detergent

- I try to avoid wearing a lot of perfume around my son because of his eczema and sensitive skin

- wash all your clothing before you or your child wears it

I never expected parenting to come with a side of guilt, no matter what I choose to do. 

My whole life pre-kid was devoted to being the best physician I could be and training at the top institutions in my field. After having my son, I felt the constant push and pull of wanting to be an incredible physician/entrepreneur/leader in my field and also an amazing mom. I saw all these inspirational quotes on IG saying that women should do it all and I felt inadequate when I struggled to do everything I wanted at the same time. 

After returning from maternity leave, I chose to go part time, something that I felt guilty about. Then, when I moved to Seattle, I opened up my own telemedicine practice, allowing me for greater flexibility at home and more time to work on my side jobs. I can’t tell you how much guilt I felt over leaving a traditional career path. I felt guilty all the time, about not seeing as many patients as I used to, about traveling too much for work, about not pursuing that startup I was focused on prior. On and on. 

But this year I fully embraced LETTING GO of guilt. I am making the best decision for me and my family in this moment.

Moms, we are all doing the best we can right now, and nothing is permanent. The current teledermatology practice and flexibility of schedule I have suits me in this stage of life. But maybe I go back to a more traditional clinic model in the future as my family’s needs change. 

We have to let go of this idea that women can and should do it all, all at the same time. Let’s embrace accepting help, let’s acknowledge that sometimes sacrifices must be made, and stepping back from one area of your life can allow another area to flourish. We are all doing our best and juggling so many responsibilities. 

So let’s let go of the guilt. Remember to give ourselves grace. And be kind to ourselves.

Let me know if you have felt this way, and let’s support each other! 

#motherhood #motherhoodunplugged #motherhoodrising #motherhoodjourney #workingmom #workingmomlife #workingmoms #mamasinmedicine

How do sheet masks and eye patches work? 🤔 

⬆️⬇️⬇️

The concept of occlusion explains how sheet masks and eye patches work. By using a physical barrier to cover the active ingredients underneath, products are absorbed better and you also don’t wipe them away as quickly.

We use this same concept in eczema therapy where we instruct patients to apply a glove or sock over their hands and feet if they have eczema there, or even cover up the affected area with Saran Wrap.

You can also put the eye mask or sheet mask in the fridge for cooling effects. 

In my view sheet masks and eye masks are nice to have luxuries, but not MUST haves.

I wish I had learned about egg freezing in my 20s. 

Or was just more aware overall of the fact that it was going to be really difficult to have a kid in residency (and that was without knowing my husband and I would be long distance for part of it).

I wish we spoke about it more in medical school or residency, which took up our 20s and 30s, after which our fertility starts to decline. 

And I wish more insurances offered to students and trainees cover fertility preservation procedures. Many friends I knew went through egg or embryo freezing because their partners had good insurance; otherwise the price of the procedures was cost prohibitive on a resident’s salary, which covered rent and then some. 

Don’t get me started on maternity leave for trainees 😨 My friends in surgery residency went back to work TWO to FOUR WEEKS after delivering their babies. 

Nearly 1 in 4 female physicians are diagnosed with infertility with an average age of diagnosis of  33.7 years.

1 in 4. 

That’s a lot higher than the general population.

Here’s to hoping we change the conversation for the next generation of #womeninmedicine! 

#ivfjourney #ivfcommunity #ivfsupport #infertility #infertilityawareness #ivf

Why do we constantly talk about not using heat styling tools on wet hair and the importance of heat protectants?

When you apply a flat iron to wet hair, the liquid 💧 in your hair gets converted to gas 🌬. 

What happens when liquid becomes gas? 

It expands! 😱

There’s not that much room for expansion in strands of hair so it shatters or bursts 💥 your hair. 

Over time this may cause dry brittle rough hair that’s prone to breakage.

Definitely use a heat protectant even if you’re flat ironing DRY hair! You want to protect your hair from heat as much as you can. Lately I’ve been liking heat protectant detangling sprays like the @kerastase_official genesys which helps condition my dry damaged hair too
